Name: Observation_Information
Description: The Observation_Information class provides information about a science observation.

Name: mission_phase_name
Description: The mission_phase_name identifies a time period within the mission.

Name: Arrival
Description: This phase starts three months prior to JOI and includes two sub-phases: Jupiter Approach and Jupiter Orbit Capture. Activities include navigation maneuvers to achieve Jupiter orbit capture.

Name: Disposal
Description: This phase starts 30 days after the last targeted closest approach of Europa. Activities include preparation for impact with Jupiter.

Name: Interplanetary Cruise
Description: This phase starts one day after launch and includes two sub-phases: Inner Cruise and Outer Cruise. Activity includes flight system characterization and navigating to the Mars and Earth gravity assists along with periodic maintenance, calibrations, and navigation activities.

Name: Launch
Description: This phase includes include launch, initial acquisition, solar array deployment, establishment of power-positive attitude, and re-establishing telemetry.

Name: Tour
Description: This phase starts eight hours after perijove and includes four sub-phases: Transition to Europa Campaign 1, Europa Campaign 1, Transition to Europa Campaign 2 and Europa Campaign 2. Activities include positioning for and execution of close flybys of Europa, Ganymede and Callisto.

Name: orbit_number
Description: The orbit_number attribute identifies the number of the orbital revolution of the spacecraft around Jupiter. Prior to JOI (i.e., from launch through cruise including gravity assists), the orbit value will be 0. After JOI, starting with the first apojove, the value will increase by 1 with each revolution around Jupiter incrementing at each subsequent apojove.

Name: encounter_id
Description: The Playback and Flyby periods together comprise an Encounter, defined as the period of time during the Tour beginning two days before the targeted closest approach of a Jovian moon, and ending two days before the next targeted closest approach of a Jovian moon. While most Jupiter orbits include a targeted flyby, there are some phasing orbits without a targeted flyby; in these cases, an encounter will span more than one orbit. Valid values consist of a three-character identifier (e.g., EO1, G02, etc.) where "E01" indicates the first encounter with Europa and "G02" indicates the second encounter with Ganymede and so on. There is one more additional special value of "XXX" representing data collected during cruise up until the first encounter.

Name: aid
Description: A hexadecimal representation of the Accountability Identifier (AID) which serves as a globally unique identifier across all instruments and mission phases for an observational activity onboard the spacecraft. Data tagged with a given AID is collected into an Accountable Data Product (ADP) on the ground and will result in one or more associated PDS data products in the archive. The AID is a 32-bit unsigned integer which contains three fields: Instrument ID (4-bits), Orbit Number (9-bits) and Data Acquisition ID (19-bits). The hexadecimal string value is prefixed with “0x”.

Name: product_type
Description: The product_type attribute indicates the processing level of an individual data product.

Name: Calibrated
Description: Data converted to physical units, which makes values independent of the instrument.

Name: Derived
Description: Results that have been distilled from one or more calibrated data products (for example, maps, gravity or magnetic fields, or ring particle size distributions). Supplementary data, such as calibration tables or tables of viewing geometry, used to interpret observational data should also be classified as "derived" data if not easily matched to one of the other categories.

Name: Partially Processed
Description: Data that have been processed beyond the raw level but which have not yet reached calibrated status.

Name: Raw
Description: Original data from an instrument. If compression, reformatting, packetization, or other translation has been applied to facilitate data transmission or storage, those processes will be reversed so that the archived data are in a PDS approved archive format.

Name: product_version_id
Description: The product_version_id attribute identifies the version of an individual data product.

Name: producer_institution_name
Description: The producer_institution_name attribute identifies a university, research center, NASA center, or other institution associated with the production of a data product.

Name: release_number
Description: Release_number is the number of a scheduled release of data from PDS. The first data release would be Release 1. The release_number for a given product is always the first release in which it appears, and does not change if the product is revised later.

Name: spacecraft_clock_start_count
Description: The spacecraft_clock_start_count attribute provides the value of the spacecraft clock at the actual start of image acquisition. There may be small inconsistencies with start_date_time due to varying correlation between UTC and the spacecraft clock. For purposes of data analysis the spacecraft clock value should be used. The format of this field is compatible with the NAIF Toolkit software where s = seconds converted from the clock's coarse counter and m = seconds converted from the clock's fine counter.

Name: spacecraft_clock_stop_count
Description: The spacecraft_clock_stop_count attribute provides the value of the spacecraft clock at the actual end of image acquisition. There may be small inconsistencies with stop_date_time due to varying correlation between UTC and the spacecraft clock. For purposes of data analysis the spacecraft clock value should be used. The format of this field is compatible with the NAIF Toolkit software where s = seconds converted from the clock's coarse counter and m = seconds converted from the clock's fine counter.

Name: spacecraft_clock_count_partition
Description: The spacecraft_clock_count_partition attribute indicates the clock partition active for the spacecraft_clock_start_count and spacecraft_clock_stop_count attributes.

Name: rationale_desc
Description: The rationale_desc attribute describes the rationale for performing a particular observation.

Name: data_quality_id
Description: The data_quality_id attribute provides a numeric key which identifies the quality of data available for a particular time period. The data_quality_id scheme is unique to a given instrument and is described by the associated data_quality_desc attribute.

Name: data_quality_desc
Description: The data_quality_desc attribute describes the data qualities associated with a data_quality_id attribute.

Name: EIS_Parameters
Description: The class contains all the instrument specific attributes for the EIS WAC and NAC.

Name: upload_id
Description: The upload_id attribute describes a spacecraft command set that is associated with the given data product.

Name: mode
Description: Indicates whether the EIS detector was commanded to take images in framing or pushbroom mode.

Name: FRAMING
Description: EIS commanded to take images in framing mode.

Name: PUSHBROOM
Description: EIS commanded to take images in pushbroom mode.

Name: gain
Description: Gain state of the EIS detector when the image was taken.

Name: HIGH
Description: EIS in high gain state.

Name: LOW
Description: EIS in low gain state.

Name: detector_temp
Description: measurement obtained by EIS detector temperature sensor

Name: fpm_temp1
Description: measurement obtained by EIS focal plane module (FPM) temperature sensor 1

Name: fpm_temp2
Description: measurement obtained by EIS focal plane module (FPM) temperature sensor 2

Name: frame_capture_start_count
Description: timestamp of the EIS Digital board (DB) receipt of the first detector line read out for a given frame. The detector can read out lines from multiple colors in the same frame and send each color to a separate TDI collection in memory where each TDI collection is associated with a unique AID. However, each AID packet will have the same frame_capture_start_count for a given frame. Thus, need this value to derive the actual starttime for a given TDI row.

Name: compression_flag
Description: Indicates if lossless compression was commanded (0=no, 1=yes)

Name: mode
Description: Indicates whether the EIS detector was commanded to take images in framing or pushbroom mode.

Name: FRAMING
Description: EIS commanded to take images in framing mode.

Name: PUSHBROOM
Description: EIS commanded to take images in pushbroom mode.

Name: filter_used
Description: Indicates the region of the detector that was used to generate an EIS image. This includes the clear and color stripe filters as well as the clear framing area of the detector.

Name: BLUE
Description: Blue filter region of the detector.

Name: CLEAR
Description: Clear filter region of the detector.

Name: FRAMING_AREA
Description: Panchromatic framing area region of the detector.

Name: GREEN
Description: Green filter region of the detector.

Name: IR1
Description: IR 1 filter region of the detector.

Name: MASK
Description: Masked region of the detector.

Name: NEARUV
Description: Near UV filter region of the detector.

Name: ONEMU
Description: One micron filter region of the detector.

Name: RED
Description: Red filter region of the detector.

Name: nframes
Description: Records the commanded number of frames for an EIS observation. A single observation may consist of multiple images with the same detector settings, therefore number of frames collected may not necessarily correlate to the number of rows in the image.

Name: gimbal_alongtrack
Description: Gimbal motor position in steps in the along-track direction of spacecraft motion. This is measured as an offset from the "home" position. 0.046875 degrees per step.

Name: gimbal_crosstrack
Description: Gimbal motor position in steps in the cross-track direction of spacecraft motion. This is measured as an offset from the "home" position. 0.046875 degrees per step.

Name: row_time_padding
Description: Additional time that the detector readout state machine will wait before moving to the next line. This value affects image exposure time.

Name: row_offset
Description: Number of readout rows to wait before reading out a given row to refresh the accumulation of photons on a given row in the detector. This allows for shorter exposure times than would normally occur if the detector waits until all rows are read out once before refreshing a given row. This value affects image exposure time.

Name: tdi_rows
Description: Number of detector rows added together by the DPU in order to perform digital time delay integration, resulting in one TDI row in the output image.

Name: Detector_Region
Description: The class contains the start/end readout rows, start/end readout columns, and row step size describing the region of the detector that is contained in an EIS image. For example, raw masked row images, where the top and bottom regions of the detector are read out in a single framing image. One instance of this object should be provided for each region that is contained in the image.

Name: readout_start_row
Description: For a framing image this is the starting row of the detector to be read out, For a TDI image this is the start of the TDI rows to be summed together.

Name: readout_end_row
Description: For a framing image this is the end row of the detector to be read out, For a TDI image this is the end row of the TDI rows to be summed together.

Name: row_step_size
Description: Row increment step size when reading from readout_start_row to readout_end_row. For a step size of 1 the detector rows are contiguous. For a step size of 2 the detector skips the readout of every other row. The value can be negative in which case the readout_start_row must be greater than the readout_end_row. The step size will be inclusive of the readout_end_row. For example, if the readout_start_row is 1 and readout_end_row is 5 and row_step_size is 2 then the rows read out are 1, 3, 5.

Name: readout_start_col
Description: The EIS detector can be commanded to read out portions of the detector in pre-defined 256 column sections known as ports. This keyword defines the starting column of the detector to be read out. Index starts at column 0 and ends at column 4095. All rows in a given EIS image will start at this column in the detector.

Name: readout_end_col
Description: The EIS detector can be commanded to read out portions of the detector in pre-defined 256 column sections known as ports. This keyword defines the ending column of the detector to be read out. Index starts at column 0 and ends at column 4095. All rows in a given EIS image will end at this column in the detector.

Name: Checkline_Row
Description: Defines the detector row and readout order for a checklines image. A Checkline_Row class is created for every detector row used as a checkline. For example, if there were 3 checklines readout for a given checklines image then this class would appear three times in the framing image label to define each checklines row. This class does NOT appear in the label for the checklines image. Instead there is a Detector_Region class for each checkline.

Name: detector_row
Description: Part of the Checkline_Row class. Identifies the detector row used in the checkline image. This row is readout multiple times in a checklines image and is used for jitter correction.

Name: readout_order
Description: Part of the Checkline_Row class. Provides an ordering of the detector rows that are used to generate the checklines image. The Checkline_Row with the lowest valued readout_order is read first, followed by the next higher readout_order, and so on. After the Checkline_Row with the highest valued readout_order is read out the instrument goes back to the lowest valued readout_order.

Name: ETHEMIS_Parameters
Description: The class contain all the instrument specific attributes for the E-THEMIS instrument.

Name: upload_id
Description: The upload_id attribute describes a spacecraft command set that is associated with the given data product.

Name: maximum_brightness_temperature
Description: Maximum brightness temperature value measured within the image.

Name: minimum_brightness_temperature
Description: Minimum brightness temperature value measured within the image.

Name: spatial_summing
Description: Onboard spatial average of NxN set of pixels, where N is the value of the keyword. SPATIAL_SUMMING = 1 implies that no spatial averaging has been applied to the image. .

Name: time_delay_integration_flag
Description: Status of onboard algorithm which applies a temporal average of successive lines in an IR image; when enabled, THEMIS TDI averages 16 detector rows to equal one line in an IR image. “ENABLED” or “DISABLED”.

Name: DISABLED
Description: The commanded time delay integration was disabled.

Name: ENABLED
Description: The commanded time delay integration was enabled.

Name: uncorrected_sclk_start_count
Description: The spacecraft clock value (in seconds) when the instrument was commanded to acquire an observation. This can differ from the spacecraft_clock_start_count by as much as 4 seconds, depending on which bands are acquired in the image.

Name: compression_flag
Description: Indicates if lossless compression was commanded (0=no, 1=yes)

Name: SUDA_Parameters
Description: The class contains all the instrument specific attributes for the SUDA instrument.

Name: event_count
Description: Number of events contained within a given AID.

Name: epoch
Description: Epoch defining the zero point of relative times in year month day UTC. For example: "YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.ssssssZ"

Name: start_time
Description: Milliseconds of the first event within this AID (time in milliseconds since epoch).

Name: end_time
Description: Milliseconds of the last event within this AID (time in milliseconds since epoch).

Name: SUDA_Event
Description: The class contains all the events for SUDA instrument.

Name: event_id
Description: Event-specific event identifier from the FPGA Header.

Name: event_time
Description: FPGA event time (time of event trigger in milliseconds since epoch).

Name: category
Description: Category determined by Flight Software Processing.

Name: aid
Description: A hexadecimal representation of the Accountability Identifier (AID) which serves as a globally unique identifier across all instruments and mission phases for an observational activity onboard the spacecraft. Data tagged with a given AID is collected into an Accountable Data Product (ADP) on the ground and will result in one or more associated PDS data products in the archive. The AID is a 32-bit unsigned integer which contains three fields: Instrument ID (4-bits), Orbit Number (9-bits) and Data Acquisition ID (19-bits). The hexadecimal string value is prefixed with “0x”.

Name: tof_peak_count
Description: Total number of TOF peaks found.

Name: tof_mean
Description: Selected TOF waveform mean.

Name: tof_var
Description: Signal to Noise ratio squared of selected TOF waveform.

Name: qv_max_amplitude
Description: Maximum amplitude (raw value) for velocity waveform (QV).

Name: qv_mean
Description: Mean of selected velocity waveform data (QV).

Name: qv_var
Description: Signal to Noise ratio squared for velocity waveform (QV).

Name: qt_max_amplitude
Description: Maximum amplitude (raw value) for target waveform (QT).

Name: qt_mean
Description: Mean of selected target data (QT).

Name: qt_var
Description: Signal to Noise ratio squared for target (QT).

Name: qt_mean
Description: Mean of selected target data (QT).

Name: qi_max_amplitude
Description: Maximum amplitude (raw value) for ion waveform (QI).

Name: qi_mean
Description: Mean of selected ion data (QI).

Name: qi_var
Description: Signal to Noise ratio squared for ion data (QI).
